      "abstract": unescape('In%20this%20paper%2c%20I%20study%20the%20early%20development%20of%20two%20organizational%20forms%3a%20credit%20unions%20and%20Morris%20Plan%20banks%20which%2c%20in%20the%20early%20twentieth%20century%20became%20socially%20acceptable%20money%2dlenders%2e%20Three%20forms%20of%20legitimacycognitive%2c%20moral%2c%20and%20pragmaticare%20important%20in%20understanding%20their%20evolution%20and%20social%20integration%2e%20Cognitive%20legitimacy%20corresponds%20to%20what%20is%20usually%20considered%20by%20organizational%20ecologists%20to%20be%20legitimacy%20as%20%27taken%2dfor%2dgrantedness%27%2e%20Organizations%20have%20moral%20legitimacy%20in%20so%20far%20as%20they%20have%20the%20moral%20approval%20of%20most%20members%20of%20society%2e%20Pragmatic%20legitimacy%20%27rests%20on%20the%20self%2dinterested%20calculations%20of%20an%20organization%27s%20most%20immediate%20audiences%27%20%28Suchman%201995%29%2e%20The%20analysis%20goes%20beyond%20previous%20work%20in%20two%20ways%2e%20First%2c%20new%20mechanisms%20of%20legitimation%20are%20introduced%20into%20models%20of%20organizational%20founding%20and%20growth%2e%20Second%2c%20organizations%20are%20assumed%20to%20be%20able%20to%20deliberately%20influence%20their%20legitimacy%20by%20their%20actions%2e%20Empirical%20tests%20combine%20quantitative%20analyses%20of%20founding%20and%20growth%20rates%20with%20a%20qualitative%20analysis%20of%20historical%20material%2e%20In%20addition%20to%20density%2ddependent%20processes%20of%20legitimation%2c%20the%20organizations%20are%20found%20to%20act%20in%20a%20social%2dmovement%2dlike%20manner%2c%20thereby%20enhancing%20their%20moral%20legitimacy%2e%20This%20increases%20their%20founding%20and%20growth%20rates%2c%20and%20gives%20them%20a%20competitive%20advantage%20over%20earlier%20forms%20of%20money%2dlending%20that%20lacked%20moral%20legitimacy%2e%20I%20also%20find%20evidence%20that%20pragmatic%20legitimacy%20is%20spread%20via%20social%20networks%2e'),
      "type": "article",
      "title": "Pathways to Legitimacy Among Consumer Loan Providers in New York City, 1914–1934",
